Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in driving tri-plane deformations from motion lies in establishing reliable, spatially coherent correspondences without relying on rigid 3D parametric models like 3DMMs or SMPL, which limit generalization across object categories and restrict fine-grained deformation learning. Inspired by Paper 1’s use of a PlaneDict to map motion to tri-plane bases and Paper 2’s emphasis on explicit point trajectory correspondence, I recognize that current methods either depend on strong priors or fail to model local deformation fields efficiently. A key insight is that motion descriptors—such as optical flow, keypoint trajectories, or motion vectors—encode rich spatio-temporal dynamics that can be leveraged to *implicitly* learn how different regions of the tri-plane should deform, without requiring an intermediate 3D parametric representation. However, directly regressing deformations from global motion vectors leads to spatially inconsistent warps. To overcome this, I propose a novel architecture that learns to predict *spatially adaptive deformation kernels* conditioned on localized motion descriptors. This approach diverges from prior work by decoupling global motion understanding from local feature modulation, enabling high-fidelity, category-agnostic deformation learning. Unlike Paper 3, which relies on mesh-based geometric contrastive learning, our method operates entirely in the neural feature space of tri-planes, making it applicable beyond meshes to general 3D scenes. The innovation lies in combining motion-sensitive attention with kernel modulation to enable fine-grained, content-aware tri-plane deformations—offering both efficiency and expressiveness.

